'''Brad Treliving''' (born August 18, 1969) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[defenceman]], and current [[general manager (ice hockey)|general manager]] for the [[Calgary Flames]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).

In 1996, Treliving co-founded the [[Western Professional Hockey League]] (WPHL), and he performed an integral role in the 2001 merger of the [[Central Hockey League]] (CHL) and WPHL. In 2003, he became assistant general manager of the [[Phoenix Coyotes]] under [[Don Maloney]], while also serving as the GM for the team's [[American Hockey League]] affiliate, the [[San Antonio Rampage]].<ref name="nhl">{{cite web |url=http://coyotes.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=32690 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914065955/http://coyotes.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=32690 |archivedate=2011-09-14 |title=BRAD TRELIVING - ASSISTANT GENERAL MANAGER - Phoenix Coyotes - Team|publisher=coyotes.nhl.com |accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> He held both positions until April 28, 2014, when Calgary Flames' president [[Brian Burke (ice hockey)|Brian Burke]] hired Treliving to be the new general manager for the Flames.<ref>http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=716880&navid=nhl:topheads</ref>

He is the son of Canadian businessman [[Jim Treliving]].<ref name="Brad Treliving Named General Manager of Flames">{{cite web|title=Brad Treliving excited to be new Flames GM|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/brad-treliving-excited-to-be-new-flames-gm-1.2624323|publisher=CBC}}</ref>

